<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-22T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-22T02:00:00-05:00" n="389" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d389">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7–2244: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-22T14:00:00+07:00">July 22,
                                1944—2 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received July 22—11:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1275. Rice at Sian telegraphs 18th and 20th [that] Chen Cheng being placed in
                        command reorganized 1st War Zone comprising Honan and Shensi provinces with
                        HQ [at] Sian. Chen has shown in press interviews conciliatory attitude
                        toward Communist question, asserting he will work to lessen Kmt–Communist
                        tension, seek political rather than military settlement, and will attempt
                        relax present tight blockade.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>